WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.680
I'm a science policy analyst at the National Institutes of Health.

00:00:09.680 --> 00:00:13.680
For those of you that don't know, the NIH is the largest funder of biomedical research

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:15.280
in the world.

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:22.480
It consists of 27 different institutes, each with a different focus on human health.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:28.440
I work at one of those institutes, the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases.

00:00:28.440 --> 00:00:33.360
This guy may look familiar, you may even own a bobblehead or a pair of Dr. Fauci socks,

00:00:33.360 --> 00:00:40.000
but he's the director of NIAID and has been for almost the past 40 years.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.380
And NIAID's mission is to fund research in infectious diseases, biodefense, and immune-mediated

00:00:46.380 --> 00:00:50.480
diseases such as asthma and allergy.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:56.279
So a little bit about myself, I was a cancer researcher for a little over a decade.

00:00:56.320 --> 00:01:00.799
I started at the University of Arizona Cancer Center and then I moved to the National Cancer

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:03.360
Institute in Bethesda, Maryland.

00:01:03.360 --> 00:01:08.120
I tell you this because I beg you, please know infectious disease questions, you'll

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:11.080
be disappointed.

00:01:11.080 --> 00:01:15.559
But while at the NCI, I developed a love for science policy.

00:01:15.559 --> 00:01:20.839
I then left the lab and started a new position at NIAID in the data analytics and research

00:01:20.839 --> 00:01:22.120
branch.

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:26.120
And there I was introduced to R and all of the tools and packages that I'll be talking

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:29.000
about today.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.559
So when I joined NIAID, I joined a very small team, it was me and two other analysts, and

00:01:34.559 --> 00:01:39.959
I kind of felt like this is how I felt the team was.

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:45.559
We were small and scrappy, but we really wanted to have an impact on a large organization

00:01:45.559 --> 00:01:46.940
like NIAID.

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:51.459
And today I'm going to tell you about how we use Shiny to support NIAID and make our

00:01:51.459 --> 00:01:55.480
team a lot more efficient as well.

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:58.959
So the first example I want to give you is a Shiny dashboard to hit research funding

00:01:58.959 --> 00:02:00.959
targets.

00:02:00.959 --> 00:02:04.239
So why do we have funding targets for a specific research area?

00:02:04.239 --> 00:02:06.879
First, we're a government organization.

00:02:06.879 --> 00:02:11.119
So Congress can tell us, we'd like you to spend this amount of money on this research

00:02:11.119 --> 00:02:12.119
area.

00:02:12.119 --> 00:02:14.080
So it can be congressionally mandated.

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:19.800
We also sometimes receive targeted funding aside from the NIH budget.

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:24.580
One example of this recently was Operation Warp Speed for COVID vaccine development.

00:02:24.679 --> 00:02:30.039
And finally, NIAID leadership can also set funding goals based on NIAID's mission and

00:02:30.039 --> 00:02:32.839
priorities at the time.

00:02:32.839 --> 00:02:36.479
But when I first got involved in this process, I found out it was a lot more complex than

00:02:36.479 --> 00:02:38.699
I originally imagined.

00:02:38.699 --> 00:02:43.919
So in some research areas that we're tracking, there are over 700 different projects.

00:02:43.919 --> 00:02:48.720
These are grants and contracts that represent a lot of different moving parts.

00:02:48.720 --> 00:02:52.419
To give you an idea, in some of these areas, we're tracking over half a billion dollars

00:02:52.419 --> 00:02:54.160
worth of funding.

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:59.479
And another added layer of complexity is that at NIH, we receive grant applications

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:00.880
throughout the year.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:05.880
So we're stuck making important funding decisions at the beginning of the year when we don't

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:08.000
have all of the data available to us.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:12.039
So we don't have all of the grants that we're going to fund that year.

00:03:12.039 --> 00:03:15.880
But I wanted to use an analogy to help understand this process.

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:20.679
So you can imagine that hitting these research funding targets are sort of like a road trip.

00:03:20.679 --> 00:03:24.720
So on a road trip, you have to know exactly where you are at any given point and how you're

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:29.080
going to get to your destination, otherwise you're going to get lost.

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:30.600
But we all know it's not that easy.

00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:34.199
Sometimes things come along that make it difficult to get where you want to go.

00:03:34.199 --> 00:03:39.419
I'm thinking of one specific road trip I took moving from Tucson to Bethesda, Maryland.

00:03:39.419 --> 00:03:42.660
On this road trip, I got a flat tire.

00:03:42.660 --> 00:03:45.800
My air conditioning broke in the middle of a heat wave.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:52.199
And I had a very vocal, very disgruntled cat in the backseat for 2,300 miles.

00:03:52.199 --> 00:03:56.279
But today I want to talk about the challenges that we faced hitting these research funding

00:03:56.279 --> 00:04:00.699
targets and how we use Shiny to address those challenges.

00:04:00.699 --> 00:04:04.639
So first, like I said, there's a lot of different moving parts.

00:04:04.639 --> 00:04:08.080
There's a lot of people involved in this process throughout the Institute.

00:04:08.080 --> 00:04:12.320
I immediately found out that there were a lot of competing estimates, right?

00:04:12.320 --> 00:04:14.399
Everybody had their own idea of where we were.

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:17.640
So it's like if you're on a road trip and you know you're in Dallas, somebody else thinks

00:04:17.640 --> 00:04:21.440
you're in El Paso, and another person thinks that you're in Utah.

00:04:21.440 --> 00:04:26.559
And nobody can agree on where you're at at the moment.

00:04:26.559 --> 00:04:28.480
So it was really frustrating.

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:33.839
Even worse is when people would come to me with funding estimates and have no details.

00:04:33.839 --> 00:04:38.160
So it's like somebody saying we're in Missouri, and I'm like, there's no chance we're in Missouri.

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:40.239
You took a wrong exit somewhere.

00:04:40.239 --> 00:04:41.239
How did you get there?

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:42.320
And they would have no idea.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:46.720
So my team spent a lot of time and effort trying to figure out how they came to that

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:50.380
conclusion and comparing it to our estimate too.

00:04:50.380 --> 00:04:56.440
And finally, at the beginning of this process, a lot of people were reliant on spreadsheets

00:04:56.440 --> 00:04:58.359
and emails.

00:04:58.359 --> 00:05:03.200
And this is a big problem, because you can imagine that immediately once you send that

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:05.760
email, that information is out of date.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:10.480
Because at NIH, we're constantly getting new applications and making new awards throughout

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:13.880
the year.

00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:17.480
And also, people make mistakes when you're searching your inbox.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.679
Maybe you found that email from last week or last month.

00:05:20.679 --> 00:05:24.920
So it was hard to get everybody on the same page.

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:31.640
So I created the Research Area Tracking tool to help address these questions.

00:05:31.640 --> 00:05:34.640
But how does this dashboard get us closer to our destination?

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:38.839
First, behind the scenes, I have an R Markdown document that's pulling in data from multiple

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:40.200
databases.

00:05:40.200 --> 00:05:46.000
I use dbplyr, so I never have to look at SQL coding again.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.119
And so it transforms it, it formats it, and writes it to a database for our Shiny dashboard

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:51.440
to use.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:56.239
And because I published it on RStudio Connect, I can schedule it to run daily so that the

00:05:56.239 --> 00:05:59.040
information is always up to date.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:02.799
So we've immediately made this process a lot better, right?

00:06:02.799 --> 00:06:06.220
So we have data integration, multiple data sources in one spot.

00:06:06.220 --> 00:06:08.200
The information is always up to date.

00:06:08.559 --> 00:06:14.079
And people have one source that they can go to for information, kind of like Google Maps,

00:06:14.079 --> 00:06:15.359
right?

00:06:15.359 --> 00:06:20.079
So next, I wanted to address this problem of having multiple estimates.

00:06:20.079 --> 00:06:25.920
And it seemed like everybody, people around the Institute had little pieces of the puzzle,

00:06:25.920 --> 00:06:28.359
but we could never put those together and get the big picture.

00:06:28.359 --> 00:06:32.519
So in the dashboard, I made all of the data available.

00:06:32.519 --> 00:06:38.959
So you can see every single project that's included or not included in our estimate.

00:06:38.959 --> 00:06:43.519
So this is almost like having turn-by-turn directions showing you exactly where we are

00:06:43.519 --> 00:06:46.440
and how we're going to get to our goal.

00:06:46.440 --> 00:06:51.600
We've made this data available to be downloaded at any point for any user.

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:54.799
We also wanted this to be a platform for collaboration.

00:06:54.799 --> 00:06:58.600
So you can add and remove projects from the estimate as well.

00:06:58.600 --> 00:07:03.600
This is an example of that, where you can add a project and add a reason for that change

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:07.559
so that other users can see why you made that change.

00:07:07.559 --> 00:07:12.160
And so that the data is always up to date, the Shiny dashboard writes all of these user

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:20.519
inputs to a database so that whenever a user logs on, it's always up to date and includes

00:07:20.519 --> 00:07:23.640
all of those user inputs as well.

00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:28.000
So the benefit of this is that we've increased transparency and collaboration in this whole

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.640
process and hopefully we've gotten closer to our destination.

00:07:32.640 --> 00:07:38.839
So lastly, I wanted the dashboard to be able to make predictions based on an application's score.

00:07:38.839 --> 00:07:45.880
So at NIH, when an application comes in, it's basically reviewed by an expert panel of scientists

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.779
and they give it a score that helps us determine whether we fund it or not.

00:07:49.779 --> 00:07:54.160
So this dashboard can actually make predictions on how much we're going to fund even before

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:56.359
we've made those awards.

00:07:56.359 --> 00:08:02.320
And since this dashboard is based on Shiny reactivity, all of the graphs, the tables,

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:08.640
the high-level numbers, everything can be changed based on user input.

00:08:08.640 --> 00:08:12.559
So we've allowed users to adjust that scoring cutoff as well.

00:08:12.559 --> 00:08:17.679
So if you're in a meeting saying, I want to fund all of the applications up to this score,

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:22.440
you can actually change that in the dashboard and see how it affects the estimates so that

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:27.720
you can make these important decisions in real time.

00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:33.000
So I hope that this dashboard has made this process a lot easier and maybe a little bit

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:34.679
more accurate as well.

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:39.159
But I think in the end, my small team benefited the most, right?

00:08:39.159 --> 00:08:45.599
Because we've been able to automate a lot of these processes and really free us up to take

00:08:45.599 --> 00:08:47.440
on additional projects, right?

00:08:47.679 --> 00:08:53.359
Before we were spending so much time manually updating the data, answering questions from

00:08:53.359 --> 00:08:59.679
colleagues and making changes that we didn't have that much time to do other things.

00:08:59.679 --> 00:09:04.320
So the next example I want to give you is how we've used machine learning to classify

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:06.599
NIAID grants.

00:09:06.599 --> 00:09:09.679
So just a little background on grants at NIH.

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:12.000
There are really two main types.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.479
One starts at NIH.

00:09:13.479 --> 00:09:20.239
So we send out a request for applications, and this is when the NIH asks the scientific

00:09:20.239 --> 00:09:25.400
community to apply for funding in a very specific, well-defined area.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:29.760
We usually use these to stimulate research in really high-priority areas.

00:09:29.760 --> 00:09:33.200
The next type of application is the investigator-initiated application.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:39.359
So instead of starting at NIH, we're starting with that investigator or scientist that's

00:09:39.359 --> 00:09:41.140
running a lab somewhere, right?

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:47.299
So these make up by far the majority of our applications, greater than 85%.

00:09:47.299 --> 00:09:54.539
And so at NIH, we really have to rely on the scientific community, the creativity and ingenuity

00:09:54.539 --> 00:09:58.179
that they have to come up with innovative research ideas.

00:09:58.179 --> 00:10:02.739
And those ideas can be very broad and cross-cutting or very narrow and well-defined.

00:10:02.739 --> 00:10:06.979
But when we get those applications, these investigator-initiated ones, we don't have

00:10:06.979 --> 00:10:08.580
much information on it.

00:10:08.580 --> 00:10:14.340
Besides that, it falls in the broad research areas of NIAID's mission.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:16.780
So you can imagine that this is very difficult, right?

00:10:16.780 --> 00:10:22.020
When you're dealing with thousands of applications, how do we know how much we've funded and what

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:25.280
projects we've funded in a specific research area?

00:10:25.280 --> 00:10:26.739
So we get questions all the time.

00:10:26.739 --> 00:10:33.380
How much have you spent on HIV vaccine research or how much have you spent on tuberculosis

00:10:33.380 --> 00:10:35.020
research and what projects?

00:10:35.020 --> 00:10:38.719
And we need to be able to answer those questions.

00:10:38.719 --> 00:10:40.219
So how do we do that?

00:10:40.219 --> 00:10:43.820
The answer is we have a team for that.

00:10:43.820 --> 00:10:49.460
So every year, NIAID gets over 9,000 grant applications, and we fund about 20% of these,

00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:50.460
give or take.

00:10:50.460 --> 00:10:54.900
We then have a team of about three to six people that go through these awarded grants

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.700
and apply codes based on the research being proposed.

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:04.760
So they have over 1,300 unique codes that they can use to describe that research.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:07.039
And I've included a few examples here on the right.

00:11:07.039 --> 00:11:11.760
So they look, are they researching a specific disease like Ebola or Zika?

00:11:11.760 --> 00:11:18.340
Is the research area, you know, new therapeutics or diagnostics and so on?

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:22.200
But you can imagine with thousands of grants, this can be challenging.

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:24.260
First, it's very time intensive.

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:30.739
So they have to go through thousands of these awarded grants and read the title, the abstract,

00:11:30.739 --> 00:11:34.559
the specific aims, and describe that research.

00:11:34.559 --> 00:11:39.840
Because it's so time consuming, we only have the resources to code awarded grants.

00:11:39.840 --> 00:11:45.599
The 80% of applications that are unfunded, we don't have any information on.

00:11:45.599 --> 00:11:47.460
And they have a constantly increasing workload.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:51.039
So every year, we're getting more applications and giving out more awards.

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:55.340
And especially at the beginning of the pandemic, this was, we saw a huge increase in applications

00:11:55.340 --> 00:11:58.440
due to COVID research.

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:01.719
And finally, because it takes so much time, this usually isn't done until the very end

00:12:01.719 --> 00:12:02.719
of the year.

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:06.280
So we don't have real time data on this, which would be helpful.

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:10.840
So we thought this was a great opportunity to use supervised machine learning for grant

00:12:10.840 --> 00:12:11.840
classification.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:16.859
We had a database of thousands of grants that had been manually coded over the past decade

00:12:16.859 --> 00:12:19.479
that we could use to train machine learning models.

00:12:19.479 --> 00:12:25.840
So here's an example of a grant that's proposing to research a more sensitive diagnostic for

00:12:25.840 --> 00:12:27.419
tuberculosis.

00:12:27.419 --> 00:12:32.500
When I looked up the codes on this grant, you could see the disease was tuberculosis.

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:36.739
The research area was diagnostics, and it was a clinically focused grant.

00:12:36.739 --> 00:12:41.580
So I just want to give you one example of how we've used machine learning to classify

00:12:41.580 --> 00:12:43.580
grants based on the research area.

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:46.219
So here, it was diagnostics.

00:12:46.219 --> 00:12:51.979
But there are five categories, including therapeutic, prevention, and vaccine.

00:12:51.979 --> 00:12:59.219
So we took about 7,500 grants that had previously been manually coded and used them to train

00:12:59.219 --> 00:13:03.739
three different machine learning models, including logistic regression, support vector machine,

00:13:03.739 --> 00:13:06.380
and random forest to compare the three.

00:13:06.380 --> 00:13:13.039
We then tested these models using about 3,200 grants that had also been manually coded.

00:13:13.039 --> 00:13:18.419
And so what we found was the logistic regression was the most accurate, 88.5%.

00:13:18.419 --> 00:13:22.500
And it also did the best at predicting this relatively small category of grants in the

00:13:22.500 --> 00:13:25.760
prevention class.

00:13:25.760 --> 00:13:31.020
So we use this machine, this logistic regression model, to build a shiny dashboard for coding

00:13:31.020 --> 00:13:32.020
NIAID grants.

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:38.340
And we then expanded it to assist in coding in five additional categories.

00:13:38.340 --> 00:13:42.659
So behind the scenes, once again, we have an R Markdown document that's pulling in the

00:13:42.659 --> 00:13:47.940
data from multiple sources, making those machine learning predictions, and writing

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:49.900
this data to a database.

00:13:49.900 --> 00:13:53.700
It's constantly getting updated with new applications, new awards.

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:56.919
And this is what our shiny dashboard uses.

00:13:56.919 --> 00:14:00.260
And once again, we wanted people to be able to collaborate.

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:07.760
So it's writing user inputs in a database for future use.

00:14:07.760 --> 00:14:12.799
So here's an example of how we're incorporating user feedback.

00:14:12.799 --> 00:14:17.679
So you can actually go through each project and say whether it's relevant or not relevant

00:14:17.679 --> 00:14:21.200
to that specific area.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:24.840
We're including the machine learning score so they know the probability that that project

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:28.640
is in that area.

00:14:28.640 --> 00:14:31.820
And once again, we wanted it to be a platform for collaboration.

00:14:31.820 --> 00:14:37.440
So you can attach notes to each of these projects for other users or even yourself in the future.

00:14:38.119 --> 00:14:39.840
Here's an example of that.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:44.159
You see a tiny little envelope when a note is attached to a project.

00:14:44.159 --> 00:14:45.520
We also have tags involved.

00:14:45.520 --> 00:14:49.440
So if you don't want to write a whole note, you can just add a small tag or phrase.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:55.239
For example, if somebody has verified that project, you can just quickly add that.

00:14:55.239 --> 00:14:59.440
So we're hoping that this project will improve productivity.

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:04.080
So if previously it took five minutes to code a grant, we're hoping with a machine learning

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:08.059
prediction and a probability estimate that we can cut that time down.

00:15:08.059 --> 00:15:12.239
And even if it was one to two minutes, you can imagine that with thousands of grants,

00:15:12.239 --> 00:15:15.119
that's a very significant time savings.

00:15:15.119 --> 00:15:17.380
We also want to support data-driven decision making.

00:15:17.380 --> 00:15:22.799
So as I mentioned, 80% of our applications are unfunded and therefore not coded.

00:15:22.799 --> 00:15:28.520
But with these machine learning predictions, we can apply these codes to all grant applications.

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:33.479
And hopefully, we can identify gaps where researchers aren't applying and

00:15:33.479 --> 00:15:35.840
we can then address those gaps.

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:41.000
So I want to thank my small team for

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.479
introducing me to R and all of the tools and packages that I've shown you today.

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:50.840
I think we've definitely been able to have an outsized impact for such a small team.

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:54.280
And I hope we can use the lessons that we've learned and

00:15:54.280 --> 00:15:57.719
the tools that we've developed to continue to support NIAID in the future

00:15:57.719 --> 00:16:01.359
with their goal of to better understand, treat, and

00:16:01.359 --> 00:16:05.880
ultimately prevent infectious diseases and to improve human health.

00:16:05.880 --> 00:16:06.440
So, thank you.

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:08.260
Hopefully we'll see you next time.

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:09.859
We'll see you next time.

00:16:09.859 --> 00:16:10.760
So, thank you.

00:16:12.760 --> 00:16:13.919
Thank you.

00:16:13.919 --> 00:16:14.679
Thank you.

00:16:14.679 --> 00:16:16.000
Thank you all for coming to the talk.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:17.940
I really appreciate it.

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:19.239
Thank you.

00:16:19.239 --> 00:16:20.119
Thank you.

00:16:20.119 --> 00:16:22.840
I'm quite exterior, I'm quite irrational, I still believe that the government

00:16:22.840 --> 00:16:26.200
should do the best we can do and I believe that's the only way this country can be

00:16:26.200 --> 00:16:27.359
very free.

00:16:28.320 --> 00:16:33.679
Thank you to our spot inspectors and

